  "text": "In PNAS, Stallforth et al. [CITATION_1] use an integrative and comparative approach to address this conundrum. Differential metabolomics and chemical analysis revealed that the inedible strain of P. fluorescens (Pf-A) produces two small aromatic molecules, pyrrolnitrin and a unique chromene, which were shown to benefit host amoebae by enhancing spore production in farmer strains of D. discoideum at natural dosages, whereas spore production by nonfarmer strains was depressed in the presence of these compounds, presumably due to their toxicity. Considering its antibiotic properties (10), pyrrolnitrin may also confer competitive advantages to farmer strains of D. discoideum that carry Pf-A, through allelopathy against soil-borne pathogens. In contrast, the edible strain of P. fluorescens (Pf-B) lacks these secondary compounds, but instead produces two specific enantiomers (4′S, 4″S) of another aromatic compound, enantio-pyochelin. Because the structural genes responsible for the biosynthesis of these compounds had identical",
